      <h4 class="introduction" id="blog">The present invention is a new unmanned/pilotless vertical air lift rescue and
MEDEVAC/Air Ambulance capable vehicle having a low profile that is configured to retrieve
injured individuals and transport those individuals to a treatment center.</h4>




<h2 id="blog">Introduction</h2>
      <p id="blog">Imagine walking on patrol in a dusty Afghanistan valley when fire erupts from boulders to your flanks.  Your squad suppresses the enemy fire and the CAS vaporizes the threat with a hellfire missile.  You look behind you and find your grenadier clutching his bleeding leg. You grab your radio hand mike and immediately call in medevac.  You look back a mile at where your MRAPs are parked, watching a plume of dust rising.
<br>
      Within a few seconds, you hear a whine and a small aircraft approaches your position rapidly.  It grows in size, and flares dramatically just before it reaches you.  The 15 foot machine quickly settles in a hover, touching down on the rocky ground.  The rotors stop turning and you hear the whine of two turbines as the dust settles.  A robotic voice shouts "System Safe!  Load Casualty!" You back sling your rifle and help carry your grenadier over to the machine.
<br>
      The canopy opens as you approach and a stretcher extends.  The control panel illuminates and a simple animation tells you to strap the casualty to the stretcher and how to apply the bio monitors.  When you press the load patient button, the stretcher retracts into the machine.  The system cycles through preflight and the launch button illuminates.  You hit it with your fist and the machine voice announces "clear rotors, spooling in 5, 4, 3, 2, 1"
<br>
      As you walk clear of the aircraft, the high pitch whine of electric motors fills the air.  As the pitch builds, the machine launches into the sky, arcing off into the distance.  You continue your patrol, knowing your grenadier will be with a doctor in eight minutes, from radio call to hospital in under 15 minutes.  </p>

<h2 id="blog">The Idea</h2>
      <p id="blog"> The above concept is an absolute posibility, and I intend to make it so.  I remember watching a MEDEVAC extraction in Afghanistan from a Tactical Operations Center UAS feed.  The pilots hovered over a saddle, tracer fire tickling their belly as they tried to extract the wounded soldier on the ground.  I remember thinking to myself "there has to be a better way...why risk three lives for one?" </p>
<br>
 <p id="blog"> I toyed with the idea for a while and finally decided to put it to paper and patent it.  I wanted to build an unmanned system capable of evacuating a patient to the nearest treatment facility with minimum human intervention.  I wanted to design a networked system capable of making intelligent service decisions and route vehicles and patients to the appropriate locations.  Finally, I wanted a system which could be used remotely as a low cost air ambulance for rural areas where such service is cost or time prohibitive.  I got to work with a patent attorney and this is what I built! </p>
